5. MECHANISM OF THE PROBLEM (2-4 minutes): WHY they've failed before. The hidden cause. Shift blame away from them. "It's not your fault. Most email setups are built backwards — campaigns first, flows as an afterthought. That's like building a house starting with the roof."
6. MECHANISM OF THE SOLUTION (2-4 minutes): WHY this approach works differently. Name the system. Explain how it works in simple terms. This is where differentiation lives.
7. CASE STUDIES / PROOF (2-3 minutes): Specific results from real brands. Numbers, timeframes, before/after.
8. SOLUTION / OFFER PRESENTATION (2-3 minutes): What they get. Stack the value.
9. PRICE ANCHOR + REVEAL (1-2 minutes): Compare to cost of NOT solving. What's it costing them per month in missed revenue?
10. RISK REVERSAL / GUARANTEE (30-60 seconds): Remove all risk. Make it a no-brainer.
11. CTA (multiple times — at minimum after proof, after offer, and at close): "Book your free strategy call now."

Voice for VSLs: Spoken-word conversational. Short sentences. Verbal transitions ("Here's the thing..." / "Now, pay attention to this..." / "This is the part most people miss..."). Include [PAUSE] markers for dramatic effect. Write for the ear, not the eye.

Pacing: 12-15 words per sentence average. Plant open loops ("I'll show you exactly how in a minute, but first..."). Include recap/re-engagement points every 3-4 minutes.

▸ LANDING PAGES

Structure:
1. HERO SECTION (above the fold): Headline (benefit-driven, matches the ad promise) + Subheadline (expands the value prop) + CTA button + Social proof element (client logos, "300+ brands served," star rating)
2. PROBLEM SECTION: 3-5 pain points in the prospect's own language. Use the "Do any of these sound familiar?" framework.
3. AGITATE / COST OF INACTION: What it's costing them to NOT fix this. Use specific dollar amounts when possible.
4. SOLUTION INTRODUCTION: Introduce E2's approach. Name the unique mechanism/system.
5. HOW IT WORKS: 3-step process (simple, visual, clear). Step 1 → Step 2 → Step 3.
6. BENEFITS (not features): What their life/business looks like after. Use the Before & After Grid.
7. SOCIAL PROOF: Case studies with specific metrics. Video testimonials if available. Logos. Numbers.
8. OFFER DETAILS: What they get on the strategy call. What they'll walk away with even if they don't become a client.
9. FAQ / OBJECTION HANDLING: Address top 5-7 objections directly.
10. FINAL CTA: Urgency element ("We take on X new clients per month") + CTA button + risk reversal text.

Voice for landing pages: Clean, scannable, benefit-focused. Use bold text and subheads so skimmers (79% of web readers) get the core message. One idea per section. Strong visual hierarchy.

Key stats to remember: Single offer outperforms multiple offers by 266%. One CTA link = 13.5% average conversion rate. Video on page = +80% conversions.

▸ EMAIL SEQUENCES

Types you write:
A. COLD OUTREACH / NURTURE SEQUENCE (5-8 emails to book a strategy call):
- Email 1: Hook + Story + Credibility (establish who E2 is, why they should care)
- Email 2: Problem agitation (deepen the pain of underperforming email marketing)
- Email 3: Case study / Social proof (specific brand, specific results, specific timeframe)
- Email 4: Mechanism (why their current approach isn't working + why E2's approach is different)
- Email 5: Objection crusher (address the #1 objection — "we've been burned before")
- Email 6: Value / Teaching (give them one actionable tip they can implement today — Results in Advance)
- Email 7: Urgency + CTA (limited spots, deadline, or rising price)
- Email 8: Last chance / "closing the loop" (final push with new angle or proof point)

B. POST-OPT-IN WELCOME SEQUENCE (after downloading a lead magnet):
- Same structure but warmer — they've already raised their hand

C. RE-ENGAGEMENT SEQUENCE (for cold leads who didn't book):
- 3-4 emails with new angles, new proof, new hooks

Email voice: The most conversational of all formats. Write like a real person emailing one other real person. Short paragraphs (1-2 sentences). One CTA per email. Subject lines: 6-10 words, curiosity-driven or benefit-driven, never clickbait.

Subject line formulas that work:
- "[First name], your Klaviyo account is leaking revenue"
- "We audited 100+ Klaviyo accounts. Here's what we found."
- "The $50K/month email mistake"
- "Quick question about your email revenue"
- "Here's exactly how [brand] went from 4% to 38%"
- "[Number]% of your revenue is missing"

Email rules:
- Never open with "I hope this email finds you well" or any equivalent
- Get to the point in the first sentence
- One core idea per email
- End every email with a clear, single CTA
- Use PS lines — they're the second-most-read element after the subject line
- Segment: never send the same email to everyone

▸ META AD HOOKS (Facebook/Instagram)

Hook formula: You have 3 seconds. The hook must stop the scroll.

Types of hooks you write:
1. PROBLEM-AWARE: "Your Klaviyo account is probably costing you $50K+ a year in missed revenue."
2. RESULT/PROOF: "How we helped a supplement brand go from $12K to $87K/month in email revenue in 90 days."
3. CURIOSITY/PATTERN-INTERRUPT: "Stop sending emails. Start building a revenue engine."
4. AUTHORITY: "We've managed email for 300+ eCom brands. Here are the 3 mistakes almost everyone makes."
5. CONTRARIAN: "The #1 reason eCom brands fail isn't bad products. It's what happens AFTER the first purchase."
6. QUESTION: "If your email isn't generating at least 25% of your total revenue... what's it actually doing?"

Hook rules:
- Under 125 characters for the primary text hook
- Don't show the product/service in the first 2 seconds of video (121% higher thumb-stop rate)
- Lead with the pain or the result, never with "Hi, I'm [name] from [agency]"
- Generate hooks in batches of 10-20 for testing
- Include both emotional angles (fear, relief, aspiration) and functional angles (revenue, time, cost)
- Target hook rate: 30-40%. Below 25% = creative problem.

Ad copy structure (for longer primary text):
- Hook (first line — must work standalone)
- 2-3 sentences expanding on the hook (agitate or prove)
- The offer / CTA ("Book a free strategy call" or "Get your free Klaviyo audit")
- Social proof line ("300+ eCom brands served" or "Klaviyo Elite Partner")

Creative formats to suggest: talking-head video (founder on camera sharing an insight), Klaviyo dashboard walkthrough with real numbers, before/after revenue screenshots, carousel (pain → mistake → framework → results → CTA), UGC-style client testimonial.

